Julianne Peyton-Brene							         April 10th, 2026

My application of the Sudoku Puzzle Generator generates random, fully solved 9x9 Sudoku boards based off of a (pseudo-)
randomly generated first row. After the first row, a backtracking strategy is implemented in order to fill the rest of the
puzzle’s main array. The strategy uses the solve and isValid methods.

The first row of the puzzle, stored in a 2D array of integers, is filled in by filling a secondhand array list of integer
objects with a loop–equating each occupant to the value of its index, plus 1–and then shuffling it using Java’s Collections
package to make the order random, before adding the random sequence to the first row of the puzzle. For the rest of the puzzle,
indexing through either the board’s rows or columns was used to fill in the 2D array.

The program iterates through each index of the puzzle’s array, checks if the current value is 0, and continuously checks
numbers 1-9 until it finds one that doesn’t compromise the rest of the board. It does that using the isValid method, which
verifies there’s no duplicates in the same row, column, or 3x3 subgroup of the current index. If it returns valid, it places
the number and calls itself to decide if it needs to go onto the next index, or if the board has been solved. This is
important, as the backtracking strategy goes back into the array a lot, so the board isn’t necessarily solved when the
algorithm reaches the last index.

The solve goes through every single occupant in the array after the first row and fills it with a looping number if it
doesn’t violate the row and column rules of Sudoku, which it checks using the isValid method. Then, it resets to force the
outer loops to continue with the next index. I chose to make the return statement of the method a boolean to implement a
recursive approach to keep the loops going. isValid checks to make sure the previously looped number can actually be inserted
into the current index without violating the rules of Sudoku. If the first loop detects the same number having been used in
the same row or column as the current index, it quickly denies the insertion. Else, it checks the other condition of there
not being repeats within each 3x3 grid, by checking the occupant of each index vertically and horizontally before and after
the current one. If it finds no issues, it returns true.

To test the program, I first edited the main method and manually filled in the first row with the [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9]
sequence provided in the first row of the example board in the assignment’s document. Then, I ran the program normally and
manually, visually checked that 10 different generated boards weren’t breaking the rules. Finally, I used other 9x9 Sudoku
generators from the internet, input the first row manually into my algorithm, and checked that the rest of the boards were
either the same or, at the very least, still accurate.

One major challenge I faced was deciding how exactly to go about the project, due to the free reign given to me by the simple
prompt of only generating a solved Sudoku board. However, the actual difficulty came from my decision to have it randomly
generate the first row, and continue from there. I had a lot of trouble with figuring out how to efficiently fill all 9
columns randomly, mostly because I was hesitant to use Java packages other than Arrays and ArrayList. The problem was fixed
as fast as it really should’ve been when I decided to just use Collections’ shuffle method.
